The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, May 26, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Hertz India, a car rental company, hopes to double its turnover to about Rs 100 crore in the next two years and expects to increase its fleet strength to 1,400 cars from the current size of over 600. The self-drive segment, which contributes around 2 per cent to our current revenues of Rs 50 crore, is expected to increase its share to 45 per cent by March 2006 when we expect the turnover to touch Rs 100 crore, Carzonrent CEO Rajiv K. Vij said. Carzonrent India is the sole licencee for global car rental major Hertz in India.																								 Tata Pipes, in association with Bajaj Allianz, has launched an insurance scheme, Tata Pipes Suraksha for providing house owners free insurance protection from fire and other perils for five years. The scheme, which is being initially offered in Bengal, would be extended to other states soon, Tata Pipes said in a release.																								 Kirloskar Electric Company Ltd (KECL) has bagged orders worth over Rs 75 crore for supply of DC motors, AC motors, generators and transformers during the quarter ended March 2004. The orders were from the water resources, steel, mining and petro-chemical industries, a company statement said.																								 Punjab National Bank-sponsored regional rural banks have reported a net profit of Rs 150.88 crore for the financial year 2003-04. The total deposits of 19 RRBs during the period recorded a growth of 10.7 per cent at Rs 5,446 crore and total advances grew by 19.1 per cent at Rs 2,104 crore, a PNB release said. The total business of these rural banks was over Rs 7,500 crore in the last fiscal, it said.																								 Lafarge India Private Limited, a cement major, has launched project employability, a programme designed to train rural unemployed youth and make them self-reliant. The project, launched at Khagaripara near Jamshedpur, was conceived in accordance with the companys aim to become the most-preferred partner of the community, Atul Khosla, vice-president of Jojobera unit said.																								 Shree Cement Ltd has recorded a 4.2 per cent rise in gross sales at Rs 606.92 crore in the year ended March 31, 2004 against Rs 582.42 crore in the previous year. Profit before tax stood at Rs 49.45 crore (Rs 40.22 crore). The board has approved a dividend of Rs 3 per share.																								 Praj Industries has posted an over 150 per cent rise in profit before tax at Rs 11.17 crore in 2003-04 against Rs 4.74 crore a year ago. Income from operations stood at Rs 109.5 crore (Rs 88.1 crore).																								 NIIT and Microsoft have launched Samridhi, a partnership programme for engineering colleges, to keep abreast with the latest developments in information technology. The two firms will conduct workshops in over 100 engineering colleges and IT educational institutions in 25 cities. ADVERTISEMENT
